  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated WaSH and Nutrition Assistance for Vulnerable Persons in Yobe and Borno States</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Having performed a rapid needs assessment and coordinated with government and humanitarian partners, Action Against Hunger will conduct an integrated nutrition and WaSH response to treat malnutrition and address its underlying causes through a behaviour change strategy promoting proper feeding and hygiene practices, as well as improving access to safe water and sanitation structures. The organization aims to contribute to save the lives of vulnerable people by protecting and promoting the nutrition security of these populations through nutrition, and water, sanitation and hygiene activities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Yobe State, AAH-US will expand on current work: supporting the provision of CMAM services and improving maternal and infant and young child feeding practices, and supervising the transition of 47 health facilities to the Ministry of Health. AAH-US will improve health facilities in Gulani, conduct sensitizations sessions on safe hygiene, lead solid waste management activities, and distribute hygiene kits to children. Using the care group model, the organization will discuss the above behavioural changes in meetings rooted in peer support, which will create new community norms for nutrition and WaSH practices. In Borno State, AAH-US will improve the immediate access to safe water and sanitation facilities, reducing the risk of disease and the devastating diarrhoea-malnutrition cycle. The organization will establish Water User Committees: hygiene promotion committees who will support the rehabilitation of water points and latrines, latrine construction and desludging, solid waste management, hygiene sensitization, and distribution of hygiene kits. Throughout all project activities, Action Against Hunger will continue to prioritize participation and gender needs, using industry-tested approaches to empower communities to continuously improve their health and environmental living conditions.</narrative>
  </description>
